  "text": "The purpose of this paper is two fold, clinical and technical. Using conventional survival analysis models applied to a large population data, we found previously that radiotherapy was associated with a survival advantage in that population data [CITATION_1] . In the present study we use the analysis of interaction to investigate whether the effect of post-operative radiotherapy may depend on type of surgery, stage of breast cancer, nodal status and extent of node examination. The clinical investigation is justified in view of the continuing debate on the role of radiotherapy in different subgroups of patients ( 23 ). However, in the paper somewhat more attention will be given to the presentation of the analytical steps, to give more insight into the use of the tests of interaction.",
